8"""The schema module provides the building blocks for database metadata. 

9 

10Each element within this module describes a database entity which can be 

11created and dropped, or is otherwise part of such an entity. Examples include 

12tables, columns, sequences, and indexes. 

13 

14All entities are subclasses of :class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.SchemaItem`, and as 

15defined in this module they are intended to be agnostic of any vendor-specific 

16constructs. 

17 

18A collection of entities are grouped into a unit called 

19:class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.MetaData`. MetaData serves as a logical grouping of 

20schema elements, and can also be associated with an actual database connection 

21such that operations involving the contained elements can contact the database 

22as needed. 

23 

24Two of the elements here also build upon their "syntactic" counterparts, which 

25are defined in :class:`~sqlalchemy.sql.expression.`, specifically 

26:class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.Table` and :class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.Column`. 

27Since these objects are part of the SQL expression language, they are usable 

28as components in SQL expressions. 

29 

30"""

165class Table(DialectKWArgs, SchemaItem, TableClause): 

166 r"""Represent a table in a database. 

167 

168 e.g.:: 

169 

170 mytable = Table("mytable", metadata, 

171 Column('mytable_id', Integer, primary_key=True), 

172 Column('value', String(50)) 

173 ) 

174 

175 The :class:`.Table` object constructs a unique instance of itself based 

176 on its name and optional schema name within the given 

177 :class:`.MetaData` object. Calling the :class:`.Table` 

178 constructor with the same name and same :class:`.MetaData` argument 

179 a second time will return the *same* :class:`.Table` object - in this way 

180 the :class:`.Table` constructor acts as a registry function. 

181 

182 .. seealso:: 

183 

184 :ref:`metadata_describing` - Introduction to database metadata 

185 

186 Constructor arguments are as follows: 

187 

188 :param name: The name of this table as represented in the database. 

189 

190 The table name, along with the value of the ``schema`` parameter, 

191 forms a key which uniquely identifies this :class:`.Table` within 

192 the owning :class:`.MetaData` collection. 

193 Additional calls to :class:`.Table` with the same name, metadata, 

194 and schema name will return the same :class:`.Table` object. 

195 

196 Names which contain no upper case characters 

197 will be treated as case insensitive names, and will not be quoted 

198 unless they are a reserved word or contain special characters. 

199 A name with any number of upper case characters is considered 

200 to be case sensitive, and will be sent as quoted. 

201 

202 To enable unconditional quoting for the table name, specify the flag 

203 ``quote=True`` to the constructor, or use the :class:`.quoted_name` 

204 construct to specify the name. 

205 

206 :param metadata: a :class:`.MetaData` object which will contain this 

207 table. The metadata is used as a point of association of this table 

208 with other tables which are referenced via foreign key. It also 

209 may be used to associate this table with a particular 

210 :class:`.Connectable`. 

211 

212 :param \*args: Additional positional arguments are used primarily 

213 to add the list of :class:`.Column` objects contained within this 

214 table. Similar to the style of a CREATE TABLE statement, other 

215 :class:`.SchemaItem` constructs may be added here, including 

216 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint`, and :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint`. 

217 

218 :param autoload: Defaults to False, unless :paramref:`.Table.autoload_with` 

219 is set in which case it defaults to True; :class:`.Column` objects 

220 for this table should be reflected from the database, possibly 

221 augmenting or replacing existing :class:`.Column` objects that were 

222 explicitly specified. 

223 

224 .. versionchanged:: 1.0.0 setting the :paramref:`.Table.autoload_with` 

225 parameter implies that :paramref:`.Table.autoload` will default 

226 to True. 

227 

228 .. seealso:: 

229 

230 :ref:`metadata_reflection_toplevel` 

231 

232 :param autoload_replace: Defaults to ``True``; when using 

233 :paramref:`.Table.autoload` 

234 in conjunction with :paramref:`.Table.extend_existing`, indicates 

235 that :class:`.Column` objects present in the already-existing 

236 :class:`.Table` object should be replaced with columns of the same 

237 name retrieved from the autoload process. When ``False``, columns 

238 already present under existing names will be omitted from the 

239 reflection process. 

240 

241 Note that this setting does not impact :class:`.Column` objects 

242 specified programmatically within the call to :class:`.Table` that 

243 also is autoloading; those :class:`.Column` objects will always 

244 replace existing columns of the same name when 

245 :paramref:`.Table.extend_existing` is ``True``. 

246 

247 .. seealso:: 

248 

249 :paramref:`.Table.autoload` 

250 

251 :paramref:`.Table.extend_existing` 

252 

253 :param autoload_with: An :class:`.Engine` or :class:`.Connection` object 

254 with which this :class:`.Table` object will be reflected; when 

255 set to a non-None value, it implies that :paramref:`.Table.autoload` 

256 is ``True``. If left unset, but :paramref:`.Table.autoload` is 

257 explicitly set to ``True``, an autoload operation will attempt to 

258 proceed by locating an :class:`.Engine` or :class:`.Connection` bound 

259 to the underlying :class:`.MetaData` object. 

260 

261 .. seealso:: 

262 

263 :paramref:`.Table.autoload` 

264 

265 :param extend_existing: When ``True``, indicates that if this 

266 :class:`.Table` is already present in the given :class:`.MetaData`, 

267 apply further arguments within the constructor to the existing 

268 :class:`.Table`. 

269 

270 If :paramref:`.Table.extend_existing` or 

271 :paramref:`.Table.keep_existing` are not set, and the given name 

272 of the new :class:`.Table` refers to a :class:`.Table` that is 

273 already present in the target :class:`.MetaData` collection, and 

274 this :class:`.Table` specifies additional columns or other constructs 

275 or flags that modify the table's state, an 

276 error is raised. The purpose of these two mutually-exclusive flags 

277 is to specify what action should be taken when a :class:`.Table` 

278 is specified that matches an existing :class:`.Table`, yet specifies 

279 additional constructs. 

280 

281 :paramref:`.Table.extend_existing` will also work in conjunction 

282 with :paramref:`.Table.autoload` to run a new reflection 

283 operation against the database, even if a :class:`.Table` 

284 of the same name is already present in the target 

285 :class:`.MetaData`; newly reflected :class:`.Column` objects 

286 and other options will be added into the state of the 

287 :class:`.Table`, potentially overwriting existing columns 

288 and options of the same name. 

289 

290 As is always the case with :paramref:`.Table.autoload`, 

291 :class:`.Column` objects can be specified in the same :class:`.Table` 

292 constructor, which will take precedence. Below, the existing 

293 table ``mytable`` will be augmented with :class:`.Column` objects 

294 both reflected from the database, as well as the given :class:`.Column` 

295 named "y":: 

296 

297 Table("mytable", metadata, 

298 Column('y', Integer), 

299 extend_existing=True, 

300 autoload=True, 

301 autoload_with=engine 

302 ) 

303 

304 .. seealso:: 

305 

306 :paramref:`.Table.autoload` 

307 

308 :paramref:`.Table.autoload_replace` 

309 

310 :paramref:`.Table.keep_existing` 

311 

312 

313 :param implicit_returning: True by default - indicates that 

314 RETURNING can be used by default to fetch newly inserted primary key 

315 values, for backends which support this. Note that 

316 create_engine() also provides an implicit_returning flag. 

317 

318 :param include_columns: A list of strings indicating a subset of 

319 columns to be loaded via the ``autoload`` operation; table columns who 

320 aren't present in this list will not be represented on the resulting 

321 ``Table`` object. Defaults to ``None`` which indicates all columns 

322 should be reflected. 

323 

324 :param resolve_fks: Whether or not to reflect :class:`.Table` objects 

325 related to this one via :class:`.ForeignKey` objects, when 

326 :paramref:`.Table.autoload` or :paramref:`.Table.autoload_with` is 

327 specified. Defaults to True. Set to False to disable reflection of 

328 related tables as :class:`.ForeignKey` objects are encountered; may be 

329 used either to save on SQL calls or to avoid issues with related tables 

330 that can't be accessed. Note that if a related table is already present 

331 in the :class:`.MetaData` collection, or becomes present later, a 

332 :class:`.ForeignKey` object associated with this :class:`.Table` will 

333 resolve to that table normally. 

334 

335 .. versionadded:: 1.3 

336 

337 .. seealso:: 

338 

339 :paramref:`.MetaData.reflect.resolve_fks` 

340 

341 

342 :param info: Optional data dictionary which will be populated into the 

343 :attr:`.SchemaItem.info` attribute of this object. 

344 

345 :param keep_existing: When ``True``, indicates that if this Table 

346 is already present in the given :class:`.MetaData`, ignore 

347 further arguments within the constructor to the existing 

348 :class:`.Table`, and return the :class:`.Table` object as 

349 originally created. This is to allow a function that wishes 

350 to define a new :class:`.Table` on first call, but on 

351 subsequent calls will return the same :class:`.Table`, 

352 without any of the declarations (particularly constraints) 

353 being applied a second time. 

354 

355 If :paramref:`.Table.extend_existing` or 

356 :paramref:`.Table.keep_existing` are not set, and the given name 

357 of the new :class:`.Table` refers to a :class:`.Table` that is 

358 already present in the target :class:`.MetaData` collection, and 

359 this :class:`.Table` specifies additional columns or other constructs 

360 or flags that modify the table's state, an 

361 error is raised. The purpose of these two mutually-exclusive flags 

362 is to specify what action should be taken when a :class:`.Table` 

363 is specified that matches an existing :class:`.Table`, yet specifies 

364 additional constructs. 

365 

366 .. seealso:: 

367 

368 :paramref:`.Table.extend_existing` 

369 

370 :param listeners: A list of tuples of the form ``(<eventname>, <fn>)`` 

371 which will be passed to :func:`.event.listen` upon construction. 

372 This alternate hook to :func:`.event.listen` allows the establishment 

373 of a listener function specific to this :class:`.Table` before 

374 the "autoload" process begins. Particularly useful for 

375 the :meth:`.DDLEvents.column_reflect` event:: 

376 

377 def listen_for_reflect(table, column_info): 

378 "handle the column reflection event" 

379 # ... 

380 

381 t = Table( 

382 'sometable', 

383 autoload=True, 

384 listeners=[ 

385 ('column_reflect', listen_for_reflect) 

386 ]) 

387 

388 :param mustexist: When ``True``, indicates that this Table must already 

389 be present in the given :class:`.MetaData` collection, else 

390 an exception is raised. 

391 

392 :param prefixes: 

393 A list of strings to insert after CREATE in the CREATE TABLE 

394 statement. They will be separated by spaces. 

395 

396 :param quote: Force quoting of this table's name on or off, corresponding 

397 to ``True`` or ``False``. When left at its default of ``None``, 

398 the column identifier will be quoted according to whether the name is 

399 case sensitive (identifiers with at least one upper case character are 

400 treated as case sensitive), or if it's a reserved word. This flag 

401 is only needed to force quoting of a reserved word which is not known 

402 by the SQLAlchemy dialect. 

403 

404 :param quote_schema: same as 'quote' but applies to the schema identifier. 

405 

406 :param schema: The schema name for this table, which is required if 

407 the table resides in a schema other than the default selected schema 

408 for the engine's database connection. Defaults to ``None``. 

409 

410 If the owning :class:`.MetaData` of this :class:`.Table` specifies its 

411 own :paramref:`.MetaData.schema` parameter, then that schema name will 

412 be applied to this :class:`.Table` if the schema parameter here is set 

413 to ``None``. To set a blank schema name on a :class:`.Table` that 

414 would otherwise use the schema set on the owning :class:`.MetaData`, 

415 specify the special symbol :attr:`.BLANK_SCHEMA`. 

416 

417 .. versionadded:: 1.0.14 Added the :attr:`.BLANK_SCHEMA` symbol to 

418 allow a :class:`.Table` to have a blank schema name even when the 

419 parent :class:`.MetaData` specifies :paramref:`.MetaData.schema`. 

420 

421 The quoting rules for the schema name are the same as those for the 

422 ``name`` parameter, in that quoting is applied for reserved words or 

423 case-sensitive names; to enable unconditional quoting for the schema 

424 name, specify the flag ``quote_schema=True`` to the constructor, or use 

425 the :class:`.quoted_name` construct to specify the name. 

426 

427 :param useexisting: the same as :paramref:`.Table.extend_existing`. 

428 

429 :param comment: Optional string that will render an SQL comment on table 

430 creation. 

431 

432 .. versionadded:: 1.2 Added the :paramref:`.Table.comment` parameter 

433 to :class:`.Table`. 

434 

435 :param \**kw: Additional keyword arguments not mentioned above are 

436 dialect specific, and passed in the form ``<dialectname>_<argname>``. 

437 See the documentation regarding an individual dialect at 

438 :ref:`dialect_toplevel` for detail on documented arguments. 

439 

440 """

660 def _init_existing(self, *args, **kwargs): 

661 autoload_with = kwargs.pop("autoload_with", None) 

662 autoload = kwargs.pop("autoload", autoload_with is not None) 

663 autoload_replace = kwargs.pop("autoload_replace", True) 

664 schema = kwargs.pop("schema", None) 

665 _extend_on = kwargs.pop("_extend_on", None) 

666 

667 if schema and schema != self.schema: 

668 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

669 "Can't change schema of existing table from '%s' to '%s'", 

670 (self.schema, schema), 

671 ) 

672 

673 include_columns = kwargs.pop("include_columns", None) 

674 

675 resolve_fks = kwargs.pop("resolve_fks", True) 

676 

677 if include_columns is not None: 

678 for c in self.c: 

679 if c.name not in include_columns: 

680 self._columns.remove(c) 

681 

682 for key in ("quote", "quote_schema"): 

683 if key in kwargs: 

684 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

685 "Can't redefine 'quote' or 'quote_schema' arguments" 

686 ) 

687 

688 if "comment" in kwargs: 

689 self.comment = kwargs.pop("comment", None) 

690 

691 if "info" in kwargs: 

692 self.info = kwargs.pop("info") 

693 

694 if autoload: 

695 if not autoload_replace: 

696 # don't replace columns already present. 

697 # we'd like to do this for constraints also however we don't 

698 # have simple de-duping for unnamed constraints. 

699 exclude_columns = [c.name for c in self.c] 

700 else: 

701 exclude_columns = () 

702 self._autoload( 

703 self.metadata, 

704 autoload_with, 

705 include_columns, 

706 exclude_columns, 

707 resolve_fks, 

708 _extend_on=_extend_on, 

709 ) 

710 

711 self._extra_kwargs(**kwargs) 

712 self._init_items(*args)

886 def tometadata( 

887 self, 

888 metadata, 

889 schema=RETAIN_SCHEMA, 

890 referred_schema_fn=None, 

891 name=None, 

892 ): 

893 """Return a copy of this :class:`.Table` associated with a different 

894 :class:`.MetaData`. 

895 

896 E.g.:: 

897 

898 m1 = MetaData() 

899 

900 user = Table('user', m1, Column('id', Integer, primary_key=True)) 

901 

902 m2 = MetaData() 

903 user_copy = user.tometadata(m2) 

904 

905 :param metadata: Target :class:`.MetaData` object, into which the 

906 new :class:`.Table` object will be created. 

907 

908 :param schema: optional string name indicating the target schema. 

909 Defaults to the special symbol :attr:`.RETAIN_SCHEMA` which indicates 

910 that no change to the schema name should be made in the new 

911 :class:`.Table`. If set to a string name, the new :class:`.Table` 

912 will have this new name as the ``.schema``. If set to ``None``, the 

913 schema will be set to that of the schema set on the target 

914 :class:`.MetaData`, which is typically ``None`` as well, unless 

915 set explicitly:: 

916 

917 m2 = MetaData(schema='newschema') 

918 

919 # user_copy_one will have "newschema" as the schema name 

920 user_copy_one = user.tometadata(m2, schema=None) 

921 

922 m3 = MetaData() # schema defaults to None 

923 

924 # user_copy_two will have None as the schema name 

925 user_copy_two = user.tometadata(m3, schema=None) 

926 

927 :param referred_schema_fn: optional callable which can be supplied 

928 in order to provide for the schema name that should be assigned 

929 to the referenced table of a :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint`. 

930 The callable accepts this parent :class:`.Table`, the 

931 target schema that we are changing to, the 

932 :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint` object, and the existing 

933 "target schema" of that constraint. The function should return the 

934 string schema name that should be applied. 

935 E.g.:: 

936 

937 def referred_schema_fn(table, to_schema, 

938 constraint, referred_schema): 

939 if referred_schema == 'base_tables': 

940 return referred_schema 

941 else: 

942 return to_schema 

943 

944 new_table = table.tometadata(m2, schema="alt_schema", 

945 referred_schema_fn=referred_schema_fn) 

946 

947 .. versionadded:: 0.9.2 

948 

949 :param name: optional string name indicating the target table name. 

950 If not specified or None, the table name is retained. This allows 

951 a :class:`.Table` to be copied to the same :class:`.MetaData` target 

952 with a new name. 

953 

954 .. versionadded:: 1.0.0 

955 

956 """ 

957 if name is None: 

958 name = self.name 

959 if schema is RETAIN_SCHEMA: 

960 schema = self.schema 

961 elif schema is None: 

962 schema = metadata.schema 

963 key = _get_table_key(name, schema) 

964 if key in metadata.tables: 

965 util.warn( 

966 "Table '%s' already exists within the given " 

967 "MetaData - not copying." % self.description 

968 ) 

969 return metadata.tables[key] 

970 

971 args = [] 

972 for c in self.columns: 

973 args.append(c.copy(schema=schema)) 

974 table = Table( 

975 name, 

976 metadata, 

977 schema=schema, 

978 comment=self.comment, 

979 *args, 

980 **self.kwargs 

981 ) 

982 for c in self.constraints: 

983 if isinstance(c, ForeignKeyConstraint): 

984 referred_schema = c._referred_schema 

985 if referred_schema_fn: 

986 fk_constraint_schema = referred_schema_fn( 

987 self, schema, c, referred_schema 

988 ) 

989 else: 

990 fk_constraint_schema = ( 

991 schema if referred_schema == self.schema else None 

992 ) 

993 table.append_constraint( 

994 c.copy(schema=fk_constraint_schema, target_table=table) 

995 ) 

996 elif not c._type_bound: 

997 # skip unique constraints that would be generated 

998 # by the 'unique' flag on Column 

999 if c._column_flag: 

1000 continue 

1001 

1002 table.append_constraint( 

1003 c.copy(schema=schema, target_table=table) 

1004 ) 

1005 for index in self.indexes: 

1006 # skip indexes that would be generated 

1007 # by the 'index' flag on Column 

1008 if index._column_flag: 

1009 continue 

1010 Index( 

1011 index.name, 

1012 unique=index.unique, 

1013 *[ 

1014 _copy_expression(expr, self, table) 

1015 for expr in index.expressions 

1016 ], 

1017 _table=table, 

1018 **index.kwargs 

1019 ) 

1020 return self._schema_item_copy(table)

1023class Column(DialectKWArgs, SchemaItem, ColumnClause): 

1024 """Represents a column in a database table.""" 

1025 

1026 __visit_name__ = "column" 

1027 

1028 def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs): 

1029 r""" 

1030 Construct a new ``Column`` object. 

1031 

1032 :param name: The name of this column as represented in the database. 

1033 This argument may be the first positional argument, or specified 

1034 via keyword. 

1035 

1036 Names which contain no upper case characters 

1037 will be treated as case insensitive names, and will not be quoted 

1038 unless they are a reserved word. Names with any number of upper 

1039 case characters will be quoted and sent exactly. Note that this 

1040 behavior applies even for databases which standardize upper 

1041 case names as case insensitive such as Oracle. 

1042 

1043 The name field may be omitted at construction time and applied 

1044 later, at any time before the Column is associated with a 

1045 :class:`.Table`. This is to support convenient 

1046 usage within the :mod:`~sqlalchemy.ext.declarative` extension. 

1047 

1048 :param type\_: The column's type, indicated using an instance which 

1049 subclasses :class:`~sqlalchemy.types.TypeEngine`. If no arguments 

1050 are required for the type, the class of the type can be sent 

1051 as well, e.g.:: 

1052 

1053 # use a type with arguments 

1054 Column('data', String(50)) 

1055 

1056 # use no arguments 

1057 Column('level', Integer) 

1058 

1059 The ``type`` argument may be the second positional argument 

1060 or specified by keyword. 

1061 

1062 If the ``type`` is ``None`` or is omitted, it will first default to 

1063 the special type :class:`.NullType`. If and when this 

1064 :class:`.Column` is made to refer to another column using 

1065 :class:`.ForeignKey` and/or :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint`, the type 

1066 of the remote-referenced column will be copied to this column as 

1067 well, at the moment that the foreign key is resolved against that 

1068 remote :class:`.Column` object. 

1069 

1070 .. versionchanged:: 0.9.0 

1071 Support for propagation of type to a :class:`.Column` from its 

1072 :class:`.ForeignKey` object has been improved and should be 

1073 more reliable and timely. 

1074 

1075 :param \*args: Additional positional arguments include various 

1076 :class:`.SchemaItem` derived constructs which will be applied 

1077 as options to the column. These include instances of 

1078 :class:`.Constraint`, :class:`.ForeignKey`, :class:`.ColumnDefault`, 

1079 :class:`.Sequence`, :class:`.Computed`. In some cases an 

1080 equivalent keyword argument is available such as ``server_default``, 

1081 ``default`` and ``unique``. 

1082 

1083 :param autoincrement: Set up "auto increment" semantics for an integer 

1084 primary key column. The default value is the string ``"auto"`` 

1085 which indicates that a single-column primary key that is of 

1086 an INTEGER type with no stated client-side or python-side defaults 

1087 should receive auto increment semantics automatically; 

1088 all other varieties of primary key columns will not. This 

1089 includes that :term:`DDL` such as PostgreSQL SERIAL or MySQL 

1090 AUTO_INCREMENT will be emitted for this column during a table 

1091 create, as well as that the column is assumed to generate new 

1092 integer primary key values when an INSERT statement invokes which 

1093 will be retrieved by the dialect. 

1094 

1095 The flag may be set to ``True`` to indicate that a column which 

1096 is part of a composite (e.g. multi-column) primary key should 

1097 have autoincrement semantics, though note that only one column 

1098 within a primary key may have this setting. It can also 

1099 be set to ``True`` to indicate autoincrement semantics on a 

1100 column that has a client-side or server-side default configured, 

1101 however note that not all dialects can accommodate all styles 

1102 of default as an "autoincrement". It can also be 

1103 set to ``False`` on a single-column primary key that has a 

1104 datatype of INTEGER in order to disable auto increment semantics 

1105 for that column. 

1106 

1107 .. versionchanged:: 1.1 The autoincrement flag now defaults to 

1108 ``"auto"`` which indicates autoincrement semantics by default 

1109 for single-column integer primary keys only; for composite 

1110 (multi-column) primary keys, autoincrement is never implicitly 

1111 enabled; as always, ``autoincrement=True`` will allow for 

1112 at most one of those columns to be an "autoincrement" column. 

1113 ``autoincrement=True`` may also be set on a :class:`.Column` 

1114 that has an explicit client-side or server-side default, 

1115 subject to limitations of the backend database and dialect. 

1116 

1117 

1118 The setting *only* has an effect for columns which are: 

1119 

1120 * Integer derived (i.e. INT, SMALLINT, BIGINT). 

1121 

1122 * Part of the primary key 

1123 

1124 * Not referring to another column via :class:`.ForeignKey`, unless 

1125 the value is specified as ``'ignore_fk'``:: 

1126 

1127 # turn on autoincrement for this column despite 

1128 # the ForeignKey() 

1129 Column('id', ForeignKey('other.id'), 

1130 primary_key=True, autoincrement='ignore_fk') 

1131 

1132 It is typically not desirable to have "autoincrement" enabled on a 

1133 column that refers to another via foreign key, as such a column is 

1134 required to refer to a value that originates from elsewhere. 

1135 

1136 The setting has these two effects on columns that meet the 

1137 above criteria: 

1138 

1139 * DDL issued for the column will include database-specific 

1140 keywords intended to signify this column as an 

1141 "autoincrement" column, such as AUTO INCREMENT on MySQL, 

1142 SERIAL on PostgreSQL, and IDENTITY on MS-SQL. It does 

1143 *not* issue AUTOINCREMENT for SQLite since this is a 

1144 special SQLite flag that is not required for autoincrementing 

1145 behavior. 

1146 

1147 .. seealso:: 

1148 

1149 :ref:`sqlite_autoincrement` 

1150 

1151 * The column will be considered to be available using an 

1152 "autoincrement" method specific to the backend database, such 

1153 as calling upon ``cursor.lastrowid``, using RETURNING in an 

1154 INSERT statement to get at a sequence-generated value, or using 

1155 special functions such as "SELECT scope_identity()". 

1156 These methods are highly specific to the DBAPIs and databases in 

1157 use and vary greatly, so care should be taken when associating 

1158 ``autoincrement=True`` with a custom default generation function. 

1159 

1160 

1161 :param default: A scalar, Python callable, or 

1162 :class:`.ColumnElement` expression representing the 

1163 *default value* for this column, which will be invoked upon insert 

1164 if this column is otherwise not specified in the VALUES clause of 

1165 the insert. This is a shortcut to using :class:`.ColumnDefault` as 

1166 a positional argument; see that class for full detail on the 

1167 structure of the argument. 

1168 

1169 Contrast this argument to :paramref:`.Column.server_default` 

1170 which creates a default generator on the database side. 

1171 

1172 .. seealso:: 

1173 

1174 :ref:`metadata_defaults_toplevel` 

1175 

1176 :param doc: optional String that can be used by the ORM or similar 

1177 to document attributes on the Python side. This attribute does 

1178 **not** render SQL comments; use the :paramref:`.Column.comment` 

1179 parameter for this purpose. 

1180 

1181 :param key: An optional string identifier which will identify this 

1182 ``Column`` object on the :class:`.Table`. When a key is provided, 

1183 this is the only identifier referencing the ``Column`` within the 

1184 application, including ORM attribute mapping; the ``name`` field 

1185 is used only when rendering SQL. 

1186 

1187 :param index: When ``True``, indicates that the column is indexed. 

1188 This is a shortcut for using a :class:`.Index` construct on the 

1189 table. To specify indexes with explicit names or indexes that 

1190 contain multiple columns, use the :class:`.Index` construct 

1191 instead. 

1192 

1193 :param info: Optional data dictionary which will be populated into the 

1194 :attr:`.SchemaItem.info` attribute of this object. 

1195 

1196 :param nullable: When set to ``False``, will cause the "NOT NULL" 

1197 phrase to be added when generating DDL for the column. When 

1198 ``True``, will normally generate nothing (in SQL this defaults to 

1199 "NULL"), except in some very specific backend-specific edge cases 

1200 where "NULL" may render explicitly. Defaults to ``True`` unless 

1201 :paramref:`~.Column.primary_key` is also ``True``, in which case it 

1202 defaults to ``False``. This parameter is only used when issuing 

1203 CREATE TABLE statements. 

1204 

1205 :param onupdate: A scalar, Python callable, or 

1206 :class:`~sqlalchemy.sql.expression.ClauseElement` representing a 

1207 default value to be applied to the column within UPDATE 

1208 statements, which will be invoked upon update if this column is not 

1209 present in the SET clause of the update. This is a shortcut to 

1210 using :class:`.ColumnDefault` as a positional argument with 

1211 ``for_update=True``. 

1212 

1213 .. seealso:: 

1214 

1215 :ref:`metadata_defaults` - complete discussion of onupdate 

1216 

1217 :param primary_key: If ``True``, marks this column as a primary key 

1218 column. Multiple columns can have this flag set to specify 

1219 composite primary keys. As an alternative, the primary key of a 

1220 :class:`.Table` can be specified via an explicit 

1221 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` object. 

1222 

1223 :param server_default: A :class:`.FetchedValue` instance, str, Unicode 

1224 or :func:`~sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text` construct representing 

1225 the DDL DEFAULT value for the column. 

1226 

1227 String types will be emitted as-is, surrounded by single quotes:: 

1228 

1229 Column('x', Text, server_default="val") 

1230 

1231 x TEXT DEFAULT 'val' 

1232 

1233 A :func:`~sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text` expression will be 

1234 rendered as-is, without quotes:: 

1235 

1236 Column('y', DateTime, server_default=text('NOW()')) 

1237 

1238 y DATETIME DEFAULT NOW() 

1239 

1240 Strings and text() will be converted into a 

1241 :class:`.DefaultClause` object upon initialization. 

1242 

1243 Use :class:`.FetchedValue` to indicate that an already-existing 

1244 column will generate a default value on the database side which 

1245 will be available to SQLAlchemy for post-fetch after inserts. This 

1246 construct does not specify any DDL and the implementation is left 

1247 to the database, such as via a trigger. 

1248 

1249 .. seealso:: 

1250 

1251 :ref:`server_defaults` - complete discussion of server side 

1252 defaults 

1253 

1254 :param server_onupdate: A :class:`.FetchedValue` instance 

1255 representing a database-side default generation function, 

1256 such as a trigger. This 

1257 indicates to SQLAlchemy that a newly generated value will be 

1258 available after updates. This construct does not actually 

1259 implement any kind of generation function within the database, 

1260 which instead must be specified separately. 

1261 

1262 .. seealso:: 

1263 

1264 :ref:`triggered_columns` 

1265 

1266 :param quote: Force quoting of this column's name on or off, 

1267 corresponding to ``True`` or ``False``. When left at its default 

1268 of ``None``, the column identifier will be quoted according to 

1269 whether the name is case sensitive (identifiers with at least one 

1270 upper case character are treated as case sensitive), or if it's a 

1271 reserved word. This flag is only needed to force quoting of a 

1272 reserved word which is not known by the SQLAlchemy dialect. 

1273 

1274 :param unique: When ``True``, indicates that this column contains a 

1275 unique constraint, or if ``index`` is ``True`` as well, indicates 

1276 that the :class:`.Index` should be created with the unique flag. 

1277 To specify multiple columns in the constraint/index or to specify 

1278 an explicit name, use the :class:`.UniqueConstraint` or 

1279 :class:`.Index` constructs explicitly. 

1280 

1281 :param system: When ``True``, indicates this is a "system" column, 

1282 that is a column which is automatically made available by the 

1283 database, and should not be included in the columns list for a 

1284 ``CREATE TABLE`` statement. 

1285 

1286 For more elaborate scenarios where columns should be 

1287 conditionally rendered differently on different backends, 

1288 consider custom compilation rules for :class:`.CreateColumn`. 

1289 

1290 :param comment: Optional string that will render an SQL comment on 

1291 table creation. 

1292 

1293 .. versionadded:: 1.2 Added the :paramref:`.Column.comment` 

1294 parameter to :class:`.Column`. 

1295 

1296 

1297 """ 

1298 

1299 name = kwargs.pop("name", None) 

1300 type_ = kwargs.pop("type_", None) 

1301 args = list(args) 

1302 if args: 

1303 if isinstance(args[0], util.string_types): 

1304 if name is not None: 

1305 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1306 "May not pass name positionally and as a keyword."

1457 def _set_parent(self, table): 

1458 if not self.name: 

1459 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1460 "Column must be constructed with a non-blank name or " 

1461 "assign a non-blank .name before adding to a Table." 

1462 ) 

1463 if self.key is None: 

1464 self.key = self.name 

1465 

1466 existing = getattr(self, "table", None) 

1467 if existing is not None and existing is not table: 

1468 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1469 "Column object '%s' already assigned to Table '%s'" 

1470 % (self.key, existing.description) 

1471 ) 

1472 

1473 if self.key in table._columns: 

1474 col = table._columns.get(self.key) 

1475 if col is not self: 

1476 for fk in col.foreign_keys: 

1477 table.foreign_keys.remove(fk) 

1478 if fk.constraint in table.constraints: 

1479 # this might have been removed 

1480 # already, if it's a composite constraint 

1481 # and more than one col being replaced 

1482 table.constraints.remove(fk.constraint) 

1483 

1484 table._columns.replace(self) 

1485 

1486 if self.primary_key: 

1487 table.primary_key._replace(self) 

1488 elif self.key in table.primary_key: 

1489 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1490 "Trying to redefine primary-key column '%s' as a " 

1491 "non-primary-key column on table '%s'" 

1492 % (self.key, table.fullname) 

1493 ) 

1494 

1495 self.table = table 

1496 

1497 if self.index: 

1498 if isinstance(self.index, util.string_types): 

1499 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1500 "The 'index' keyword argument on Column is boolean only. " 

1501 "To create indexes with a specific name, create an " 

1502 "explicit Index object external to the Table." 

1503 ) 

1504 table.append_constraint( 

1505 Index( 

1506 None, self.key, unique=bool(self.unique), _column_flag=True 

1507 ) 

1508 ) 

1509 

1510 elif self.unique: 

1511 if isinstance(self.unique, util.string_types): 

1512 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1513 "The 'unique' keyword argument on Column is boolean " 

1514 "only. To create unique constraints or indexes with a " 

1515 "specific name, append an explicit UniqueConstraint to " 

1516 "the Table's list of elements, or create an explicit " 

1517 "Index object external to the Table." 

1518 ) 

1519 table.append_constraint( 

1520 UniqueConstraint(self.key, _column_flag=True) 

1521 ) 

1522 

1523 self._setup_on_memoized_fks(lambda fk: fk._set_remote_table(table))

1525 def _setup_on_memoized_fks(self, fn): 

1526 fk_keys = [ 

1527 ((self.table.key, self.key), False), 

1528 ((self.table.key, self.name), True), 

1529 ] 

1530 for fk_key, link_to_name in fk_keys: 

1531 if fk_key in self.table.metadata._fk_memos: 

1532 for fk in self.table.metadata._fk_memos[fk_key]: 

1533 if fk.link_to_name is link_to_name: 

1534 fn(fk)

1539 else:

1585 def _make_proxy( 

1586 self, selectable, name=None, key=None, name_is_truncatable=False, **kw 

1587 ): 

1588 """Create a *proxy* for this column. 

1589 

1590 This is a copy of this ``Column`` referenced by a different parent 

1591 (such as an alias or select statement). The column should 

1592 be used only in select scenarios, as its full DDL/default 

1593 information is not transferred. 

1594 

1595 """ 

1596 fk = [ 

1597 ForeignKey(f.column, _constraint=f.constraint) 

1598 for f in self.foreign_keys 

1599 ] 

1600 if name is None and self.name is None: 

1601 raise exc.InvalidRequestError( 

1602 "Cannot initialize a sub-selectable" 

1603 " with this Column object until its 'name' has " 

1604 "been assigned." 

1605 ) 

1606 try: 

1607 c = self._constructor( 

1608 _as_truncated(name or self.name) 

1609 if name_is_truncatable 

1610 else (name or self.name), 

1611 self.type, 

1612 key=key if key else name if name else self.key, 

1613 primary_key=self.primary_key, 

1614 nullable=self.nullable, 

1615 _proxies=[self], 

1616 *fk 

1617 ) 

1618 except TypeError: 

1619 util.raise_from_cause( 

1620 TypeError( 

1621 "Could not create a copy of this %r object. " 

1622 "Ensure the class includes a _constructor() " 

1623 "attribute or method which accepts the " 

1624 "standard Column constructor arguments, or " 

1625 "references the Column class itself." % self.__class__ 

1626 ) 

1627 ) 

1628 

1629 c.table = selectable 

1630 selectable._columns.add(c) 

1631 if selectable._is_clone_of is not None: 

1632 c._is_clone_of = selectable._is_clone_of.columns.get(c.key) 

1633 if self.primary_key: 

1634 selectable.primary_key.add(c) 

1635 c.dispatch.after_parent_attach(c, selectable) 

1636 return c

1649class ForeignKey(DialectKWArgs, SchemaItem): 

1650 """Defines a dependency between two columns. 

1651 

1652 ``ForeignKey`` is specified as an argument to a :class:`.Column` object, 

1653 e.g.:: 

1654 

1655 t = Table("remote_table", metadata, 

1656 Column("remote_id", ForeignKey("main_table.id")) 

1657 ) 

1658 

1659 Note that ``ForeignKey`` is only a marker object that defines 

1660 a dependency between two columns. The actual constraint 

1661 is in all cases represented by the :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint` 

1662 object. This object will be generated automatically when 

1663 a ``ForeignKey`` is associated with a :class:`.Column` which 

1664 in turn is associated with a :class:`.Table`. Conversely, 

1665 when :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint` is applied to a :class:`.Table`, 

1666 ``ForeignKey`` markers are automatically generated to be 

1667 present on each associated :class:`.Column`, which are also 

1668 associated with the constraint object. 

1669 

1670 Note that you cannot define a "composite" foreign key constraint, 

1671 that is a constraint between a grouping of multiple parent/child 

1672 columns, using ``ForeignKey`` objects. To define this grouping, 

1673 the :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint` object must be used, and applied 

1674 to the :class:`.Table`. The associated ``ForeignKey`` objects 

1675 are created automatically. 

1676 

1677 The ``ForeignKey`` objects associated with an individual 

1678 :class:`.Column` object are available in the `foreign_keys` collection 

1679 of that column. 

1680 

1681 Further examples of foreign key configuration are in 

1682 :ref:`metadata_foreignkeys`. 

1683 

1684 """ 

1685 

1686 __visit_name__ = "foreign_key" 

1687 

1688 def __init__( 

1689 self, 

1690 column, 

1691 _constraint=None, 

1692 use_alter=False, 

1693 name=None, 

1694 onupdate=None, 

1695 ondelete=None, 

1696 deferrable=None, 

1697 initially=None, 

1698 link_to_name=False, 

1699 match=None, 

1700 info=None, 

1701 **dialect_kw 

1702 ): 

1703 r""" 

1704 Construct a column-level FOREIGN KEY. 

1705 

1706 The :class:`.ForeignKey` object when constructed generates a 

1707 :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint` which is associated with the parent 

1708 :class:`.Table` object's collection of constraints. 

1709 

1710 :param column: A single target column for the key relationship. A 

1711 :class:`.Column` object or a column name as a string: 

1712 ``tablename.columnkey`` or ``schema.tablename.columnkey``. 

1713 ``columnkey`` is the ``key`` which has been assigned to the column 

1714 (defaults to the column name itself), unless ``link_to_name`` is 

1715 ``True`` in which case the rendered name of the column is used. 

1716 

1717 :param name: Optional string. An in-database name for the key if 

1718 `constraint` is not provided. 

1719 

1720 :param onupdate: Optional string. If set, emit ON UPDATE <value> when 

1721 issuing DDL for this constraint. Typical values include CASCADE, 

1722 DELETE and RESTRICT. 

1723 

1724 :param ondelete: Optional string. If set, emit ON DELETE <value> when 

1725 issuing DDL for this constraint. Typical values include CASCADE, 

1726 DELETE and RESTRICT. 

1727 

1728 :param deferrable: Optional bool. If set, emit DEFERRABLE or NOT 

1729 DEFERRABLE when issuing DDL for this constraint. 

1730 

1731 :param initially: Optional string. If set, emit INITIALLY <value> when 

1732 issuing DDL for this constraint. 

1733 

1734 :param link_to_name: if True, the string name given in ``column`` is 

1735 the rendered name of the referenced column, not its locally 

1736 assigned ``key``. 

1737 

1738 :param use_alter: passed to the underlying 

1739 :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint` to indicate the constraint should 

1740 be generated/dropped externally from the CREATE TABLE/ DROP TABLE 

1741 statement. See :paramref:`.ForeignKeyConstraint.use_alter` 

1742 for further description. 

1743 

1744 .. seealso:: 

1745 

1746 :paramref:`.ForeignKeyConstraint.use_alter` 

1747 

1748 :ref:`use_alter` 

1749 

1750 :param match: Optional string. If set, emit MATCH <value> when issuing 

1751 DDL for this constraint. Typical values include SIMPLE, PARTIAL 

1752 and FULL. 

1753 

1754 :param info: Optional data dictionary which will be populated into the 

1755 :attr:`.SchemaItem.info` attribute of this object. 

1756 

1757 .. versionadded:: 1.0.0 

1758 

1759 :param \**dialect_kw: Additional keyword arguments are dialect 

1760 specific, and passed in the form ``<dialectname>_<argname>``. The 

1761 arguments are ultimately handled by a corresponding 

1762 :class:`.ForeignKeyConstraint`. See the documentation regarding 

1763 an individual dialect at :ref:`dialect_toplevel` for detail on 

1764 documented arguments. 

1765 

1766 .. versionadded:: 0.9.2 

1767 

1768 """ 

1769 

1770 self._colspec = column 

1771 if isinstance(self._colspec, util.string_types): 

1772 self._table_column = None 

1773 else: 

1774 if hasattr(self._colspec, "__clause_element__"): 

1775 self._table_column = self._colspec.__clause_element__() 

1776 else: 

1777 self._table_column = self._colspec 

1778 

1779 if not isinstance(self._table_column, ColumnClause): 

1780 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1781 "String, Column, or Column-bound argument " 

1782 "expected, got %r" % self._table_column 

1783 ) 

1784 elif not isinstance( 

1785 self._table_column.table, (util.NoneType, TableClause) 

1786 ): 

1787 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1788 "ForeignKey received Column not bound " 

1789 "to a Table, got: %r" % self._table_column.table 

1790 ) 

1791 

1792 # the linked ForeignKeyConstraint. 

1793 # ForeignKey will create this when parent Column 

1794 # is attached to a Table, *or* ForeignKeyConstraint 

1795 # object passes itself in when creating ForeignKey 

1796 # markers. 

1797 self.constraint = _constraint 

1798 self.parent = None 

1799 self.use_alter = use_alter 

1800 self.name = name 

1801 self.onupdate = onupdate 

1802 self.ondelete = ondelete 

1803 self.deferrable = deferrable 

1804 self.initially = initially

1815 """Produce a copy of this :class:`.ForeignKey` object. 

1816 

1817 The new :class:`.ForeignKey` will not be bound 

1818 to any :class:`.Column`. 

1819 

1820 This method is usually used by the internal 

1821 copy procedures of :class:`.Column`, :class:`.Table`, 

1822 and :class:`.MetaData`. 

1823

1825 reference the original table and column name, qualified 

1826 by the given string schema name.

1831 self._get_colspec(schema=schema), 

1832 use_alter=self.use_alter, 

1833 name=self.name,

1844 def _get_colspec(self, schema=None, table_name=None): 

1845 """Return a string based 'column specification' for this 

1846 :class:`.ForeignKey`. 

1847 

1848 This is usually the equivalent of the string-based "tablename.colname" 

1849 argument first passed to the object's constructor. 

1850 

1851 """ 

1852 if schema: 

1853 _schema, tname, colname = self._column_tokens 

1854 if table_name is not None: 

1855 tname = table_name 

1856 return "%s.%s.%s" % (schema, tname, colname) 

1857 elif table_name: 

1858 schema, tname, colname = self._column_tokens 

1859 if schema: 

1860 return "%s.%s.%s" % (schema, table_name, colname) 

1861 else: 

1862 return "%s.%s" % (table_name, colname) 

1863 elif self._table_column is not None: 

1864 return "%s.%s" % ( 

1865 self._table_column.table.fullname, 

1866 self._table_column.key, 

1867 ) 

1868 else: 

1869 return self._colspec

1873 return self._column_tokens[0]

1875 def _table_key(self): 

1876 if self._table_column is not None: 

1877 if self._table_column.table is None: 

1878 return None 

1879 else: 

1880 return self._table_column.table.key 

1881 else: 

1882 schema, tname, colname = self._column_tokens 

1883 return _get_table_key(tname, schema)

1894 """Return the :class:`.Column` in the given :class:`.Table` 

1895 referenced by this :class:`.ForeignKey`. 

1896 

1897 Returns None if this :class:`.ForeignKey` does not reference the given 

1898 :class:`.Table`. 

1899

1904 @util.memoized_property 

1905 def _column_tokens(self): 

1906 """parse a string-based _colspec into its component parts.""" 

1907 

1908 m = self._get_colspec().split(".") 

1909 if m is None: 

1910 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

1911 "Invalid foreign key column specification: %s" % self._colspec 

1912 ) 

1913 if len(m) == 1: 

1914 tname = m.pop() 

1915 colname = None 

1916 else: 

1917 colname = m.pop() 

1918 tname = m.pop() 

1919 

1920 # A FK between column 'bar' and table 'foo' can be 

1921 # specified as 'foo', 'foo.bar', 'dbo.foo.bar', 

1922 # 'otherdb.dbo.foo.bar'. Once we have the column name and 

1923 # the table name, treat everything else as the schema 

1924 # name. Some databases (e.g. Sybase) support 

1925 # inter-database foreign keys. See tickets#1341 and -- 

1926 # indirectly related -- Ticket #594. This assumes that '.' 

1927 # will never appear *within* any component of the FK. 

1928 

1929 if len(m) > 0: 

1930 schema = ".".join(m) 

1931 else: 

1932 schema = None 

1933 return schema, tname, colname

2299class Sequence(DefaultGenerator):

2764class ColumnCollectionMixin(object): 

2765 

2766 columns = None 

2767 """A :class:`.ColumnCollection` of :class:`.Column` objects. 

2768 

2769 This collection represents the columns which are referred to by 

2770 this object. 

2771 

2772 """ 

2773 

2774 _allow_multiple_tables = False 

2775 

2776 def __init__(self, *columns, **kw): 

2777 _autoattach = kw.pop("_autoattach", True) 

2778 self._column_flag = kw.pop("_column_flag", False) 

2779 self.columns = ColumnCollection() 

2780 self._pending_colargs = [ 

2781 _to_schema_column_or_string(c) for c in columns 

2782 ] 

2783 if _autoattach and self._pending_colargs: 

2784 self._check_attach() 

2785 

2786 @classmethod 

2787 def _extract_col_expression_collection(cls, expressions): 

2788 for expr in expressions: 

2789 strname = None 

2790 column = None 

2791 if hasattr(expr, "__clause_element__"): 

2792 expr = expr.__clause_element__() 

2793 

2794 if not isinstance(expr, (ColumnElement, TextClause)): 

2795 # this assumes a string 

2796 strname = expr 

2797 else: 

2798 cols = [] 

2799 visitors.traverse(expr, {}, {"column": cols.append}) 

2800 if cols: 

2801 column = cols[0] 

2802 add_element = column if column is not None else strname 

2803 yield expr, column, strname, add_element 

2804 

2805 def _check_attach(self, evt=False): 

2806 col_objs = [c for c in self._pending_colargs if isinstance(c, Column)] 

2807 

2808 cols_w_table = [c for c in col_objs if isinstance(c.table, Table)] 

2809 

2810 cols_wo_table = set(col_objs).difference(cols_w_table) 

2811 

2812 if cols_wo_table: 

2813 # feature #3341 - place event listeners for Column objects 

2814 # such that when all those cols are attached, we autoattach. 

2815 assert not evt, "Should not reach here on event call" 

2816 

2817 # issue #3411 - don't do the per-column auto-attach if some of the 

2818 # columns are specified as strings. 

2819 has_string_cols = set(self._pending_colargs).difference(col_objs) 

2820 if not has_string_cols: 

2821 

2822 def _col_attached(column, table): 

2823 # this isinstance() corresponds with the 

2824 # isinstance() above; only want to count Table-bound 

2825 # columns 

2826 if isinstance(table, Table): 

2827 cols_wo_table.discard(column) 

2828 if not cols_wo_table: 

2829 self._check_attach(evt=True) 

2830 

2831 self._cols_wo_table = cols_wo_table 

2832 for col in cols_wo_table: 

2833 col._on_table_attach(_col_attached) 

2834 return 

2835 

2836 columns = cols_w_table 

2837 

2838 tables = {c.table for c in columns} 

2839 if len(tables) == 1: 

2840 self._set_parent_with_dispatch(tables.pop()) 

2841 elif len(tables) > 1 and not self._allow_multiple_tables: 

2842 table = columns[0].table 

2843 others = [c for c in columns[1:] if c.table is not table] 

2844 if others: 

2845 raise exc.ArgumentError( 

2846 "Column(s) %s are not part of table '%s'." 

2847 % ( 

2848 ", ".join("'%s'" % c for c in others), 

2849 table.description, 

2850 ) 

2851 ) 

2852 

2853 def _col_expressions(self, table): 

2854 return [ 

2855 table.c[col] if isinstance(col, util.string_types) else col 

2856 for col in self._pending_colargs 

2857 ] 

2858 

2859 def _set_parent(self, table): 

2860 for col in self._col_expressions(table): 

2861 if col is not None: 

2862 self.columns.add(col)

3322class PrimaryKeyConstraint(ColumnCollectionConstraint): 

3323 """A table-level PRIMARY KEY constraint. 

3324

3334 ... )

3357 An warning is emitted if the columns present in the

3361 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` declaration, and those columns otherwise

3366 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` in addition to columns marked as 

3367 ``primary_key=True`` now emits a warning if the lists don't match.

3370 may raise an exception in a future release. 

3371

3389 the constraint, independently of the specification of "primary key" 

3390 columns within the :class:`.Table` itself; columns marked as

3842 SQLAlchemy such as Declarative may not have similar behaviors

3905 

3906 * ``%(column_0_N_name)s`` - the name of all :class:`.Column`
